Title : Aneurin Hughes
Text : '''Aneurin Rhys "Nye" Hughes''' (born 1937) is a retired British diplomat known for his long involvement with the [[European Commission]]. He was the [[Ambassadors of the European Union|EU Ambassador]] to [[Norway]] and [[Iceland]] from 1987 to 1995 and to [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]] from 1995 to 2002.

Hughes was born in [[Swansea]], [[Wales]], and is fluent in both [[English language|English]] and [[Welsh language|Welsh]]. He attended [[Swansea Grammar School]], and also spent a year abroad in the U.S. at [[Oregon City High School]], on an [[AFS Intercultural Programs|AFS]] exchange. Hughes went on to the [[University College Wales, Aberystwyth]], graduating in 1961 with a double degree in [[Celtic studies]] and philosophy.<ref>[http://ausit.org/AUSIT/Documents/1997_jbl.pdf Aneurin Hughes: The Importance of Language Services in International Relations], The Jill Blewett Memorial Lectures, 1997.</ref> He was president of the [[Aberystwyth University Students' Union]]. He later began a [[PhD]] at the [[University of London]] on the subject of higher education in South America, which he did not complete. From 1962 to 1964, Hughes was president of the [[National Union of Students (United Kingdom)|National Union of Students]]. He succeeded another Welshman, [[Gwyn Morgan OBE|Gwyn Morgan]].<ref>[https://www.aber.ac.uk/en/development/alumni/obituaries/obituaryprofiles/drjohngwynfrynmorgan/ Obituaries: Dr John Gwynfryn Morgan], Aberystwyth University.</ref> Hughes joined the [[Foreign Office]] in 1966. He was first secretary to the [[High Commissioners of the United Kingdom to Singapore|British High Commissioner to Singapore]] from 1968 to 1970, and then first secretary to the [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to Italy|Ambassador to Italy]] from 1972 to 1973.<ref name=archive/>

In 1973, Hughes joined the [[European Civil Service]]. He was head of the Division for Internal Coordination until 1976, and then served as an advisor to the [[Directorate General for Communications Networks, Content and Technology|Director-General for Information]] from 1977 to 1980. From 1981 to 1985, Hughes was chief of staff to [[Ivor Richard]], the [[European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Inclusion]]. He was then EU Ambassador to Norway and Iceland from 1987 to 1995, and EU Ambassador to Australia and New Zealand from 1995 to 2002.<ref name=archive>[http://aei.pitt.edu/75326/ Aneurin Rhys Hughes], Archive of European Integration.</ref> Hughes remained in Australia after retiring. To coincide with the [[2003 Rugby World Cup]], the [[Government of the Australian Capital Territory]] appointed him as a liaison officer for visiting European businesspeople.<ref>[http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/helping-business-score-world-cup-2481170 Helping business to score in the World Cup], Wales Online, 13 June 2003.</ref> In 2005, Hughes published a biography of [[Billy Hughes]] (no relation), the seventh [[Prime Minister of Australia]] and a fellow Welshman. [[John Button]], writing for ''[[Eureka Street (magazine)|Eureka Street]]'', called it "a thought-provoking account of an extraordinary figure about whom we now know a great deal more than before".<ref>[[John Button]]: [https://www.eurekastreet.com.au/article.aspx?aeid=232#.WWysioiGPIU Getting to know Billy better], ''Eureka Street'', 14 May 2006.</ref>

